  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "2394750c-f3ba-80ca-b64e-ce2c396d411c",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Recommender System Type",
          "Target of Recommendation",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Initialization Method",
          "Updates to Recommendations",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Recommendation types",
          "Evaluation",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Interactive Content Platform",
          "E-Learning",
          "Hybrid Filtering",
          "Songs to practice",
          "35028 users",
          "Not Applicable",
          "Tomplay ",
          "3 embeddings:\n\nUser & item embeddings are randomly (or Xavier) initialized in the LightGCN.Item title & composer embeddings come from a pre-trained SBERT model and are averaged with the item ID embedding.Cold-start users = zero vector → single forward pass over the graph (no retraining).\n\n50 interactions seem to be enough to get a good understanding.",
          "Since it is a graph neural network, new interactions ar added to the graph and the recommendations are updated. \n",
          "The number of interactions is smaller than other common recommendation datasets.\n\nRecommender works by creating embeddings of the users and embeddings of the items. \n\nRaw logs are used to create event sequences. A graph is built with interactions as edges. Entity resolution incorporates SBERT embeddings for titles and composers, combining with item embeddings. Graph preprocessing connects similar items and adds exponential decay edge weights. Negative sampling is used to create Y.\n\nUser features are preprocessed for the baseline Heater model.",
          "Top-10 Recommendations",
          "{F1-Score: 0.24, Recall@25: 0.391, Precision@25: 0.174, HR@10: 0.990, NDCG@10: 0.826}",
          "The work uses Tomplay dataset - an educational dataset that is sometimes used by College Professors.\n\nThe authors propose a GNN-based approach based on LightGCN., which is compared against a myriad of other common RS approaches. \n\nBest performance at 1 GNN layer; connecting similar items didn’t help; sensitive to γ",
          "Validation on a single dataset.\n\nNo deployment. \n\nItem averaging may lose information (even if computationally more expedient).\n\nGraph connections of similar items does not seem to improve recommender accuracy,\n\nDataset only contains positive interactions (negatives are assumed). \n\nCold start module cannot learn → forward pass only\n\nFor cold-start evaluation: 20% new users with ≥325 interactions are chosen"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
